  "text": "Details of the surgical preparation and electrical stimulation were as reported previously [CITATION_1] . Briefly, male rats (Sprague-Dawlev. 250-350 Em) were anesthetized with urethane (1.5 &&kg, i.p.), supplemented ai needed (0.2 gm/kg) to maintain areflexia and slow-wave EEG activity, and placed in a stereotaxic apparatus on a heating pad (rectal temperature maintained at 37°C). Tracheal cannulation, lumbar suspension, and drainage of the cistema magna minimized brain pulsations due to respiration and blood pressure fluctuations. Craniotomies over auditory cortex, thalamus, and frontal cortex allowed for placement of recording and stimulation electrodes. For electrical stimulation of the NB, bipolar electrodes were placed at (in mm from bregma; [CITATION_2] ) AP -1.4 to -1.8, ML 2.0, depth -6.4 from the pia. Stimulating electrodes were also placed in the medial geniculate body (MC) of the thalamus (AP -5.8, ML 2.8, depth -5.4). Electrical stimuli consisted of 0.1 -msec-duration constant current pulses, generally 100-500 PA, delivered singly to the MG, or as a train to the NB (typically 20-100 pulses at 200/set). These stimulus loci and parameters are optimal for electrical or chemical stimulation of the cholinergic NB projection to auditory cortex, and for electrical stimulation of the MG projection to auditory cortex [CITATION_3] . Experiments were terminated by anesthesia overdose.",
